wo dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert De Hebuterne was born in 1200, in Hébuterne, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Gauthier De Hebuturne II, was 36 and his mother, Isabelle De Berles, was 21. He had at least 2 daughters with Jeanne de Ponthieu."},"et":{"1200–":"1200–Surnud","1197–1259":"1197–1259","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1188–1239":"1188–1239","1223–1255":"1223–1255","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1164–1221":"1164–1221","1180–1238":"1180–1238","1239":"1239","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1223":"1223","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1221":"1221","1188":"1188","1230":"1230","1164":"1164","1197":"1197","1180":"1180","Hébuterne, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Hébuterne, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1200–":"1200–Kuollut","1197–1259":"1197–1259","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1188–1239":"1188–1239","1223–1255":"1223–1255","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1164–1221":"1164–1221","1180–1238":"1180–1238","1239":"1239","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1223":"1223","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1221":"1221","1188":"1188","1230":"1230","1164":"1164","1197":"1197","11